article.headline: Pistons break through against Jazz in Utah
article.linkText: Pistons get first win in 10-year-old Delta Center
article.story:
SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- After losing to the Utah Jazz despite the absence of Karl Malone last Friday, Chucky Atkins and the Detroit Pistons were focused on evening the score in a place where they had never won.
Stackhouse

Atkins, Jerry Stackhouse and Cliff Robinson each had 20 points as the Pistons beat the Jazz 94-87 Tuesday night for their third straight road victory. "We came in here with one thing on our mind and that was payback. We thought that we should have beat them on our home court last week," Atkins said. As the clock was running down, Jon Barry screamed, "I love beating Utah!" It's something the Pistons rarely have been able to do, especially in Salt Lake City. But Corliss Williamson scored eight of his 10 points in the fourth quarter when the Pistons went on a game-clinching 13-3 run for their first victory ever in the 10-year-old Delta Center. "This is a hard place to win ... You always feel like you've won a game in a championship series because of the caliber of the competition and the noise of the building," Detroit coach Rick Carlisle said. The Pistons had dropped five in a row to the Jazz, including a 100-97 defeat Friday when Malone was out with the flu. Detroit hadn't won in Salt Lake City in 11 games since a 108-104 triumph on March 29, 1989. "We've been close plenty of times, but this is the first time our franchise has done it. It's a huge win for us," Stackhouse said. But the Jazz, who were led by Malone's 22 points, aren't nearly as invincible as they once were in this building. Utah is just 2-3 at home this month. "We couldn't get anything going offensively to keep the pressure on them so they cruised up and controlled the tempo the last few minutes," said Stockton, who had 20 points, seven rebounds, five assists and five steals. Stockton tied the game at 74 with 6:04 left in the fourth quarter before Willamson made two inside baskets and sparked the run that ended with the Pistons leading 87-77 with 2:05 to play. "The big thing is we started hitting some shots," Carlisle said. The Pistons have won the first three games on their five-game trip, which concludes with games against the Los Angeles Lakers and Phoenix. Detroit now has a three-game lead in the Central Division over the Milwaukee Bucks, who lost in Orlando on Tuesday night. After struggling with 33 percent shooting in the first half, the Pistons started to find their accuracy in the second half, going 18-for-30 many from long range. The Jazz outscored Detroit 36-14 in the paint but committed 19 turnovers, shot 1-for-11 from 3-point range and made just one field goal in a five minute period down the stretch. "The turnovers killed us ... it just looked like mashed potatoes out there the way we're trying to play," Utah coach Jerry Sloan said. Bryon Russell left the game after Stackhouse scratched his right eye with 5:52 left in the third quarter. The Jazz were leading 54-45. Donyell Marshall put Utah up 56-45 midway through the third quarter before Detroit went on a 19-5 run fueled by four 3-pointers, including Robinson's 26-footer to beat the third-period buzzer. "We're playing with a lot of confidence and it shows," Robinson said. Game notes
Malone passed Elvin Hayes (50,000) for second place on the minutes played list. Only Kareem Abdul-Jabbar (57,446 minutes) has played more. ... Stockton was honored before the game for becoming the first player in NBA history to record 15,000 career assists. He achieved the mark at Houston on March 10, the first game of a five-game road trip. ... Stackhouse shot 3-of-15 in the first half. ... Marshall was whistled for the seldom-called punching the ball violation in the first quarter.
